Section 5.1: Equality kinds in c# and equality operator

In C#, there are two diﬀerent kinds of equality: reference equality and value equality. Value equality is the

commonly understood meaning of equality: it means that two objects contain the same values. For example, two

o diﬀerent kinds of equality: reference equality and value equality. Value equality is the

commonly understood meaning of equality: it means that two objects contain the same values. For example, two

integers with the value of 2 have value equality. Reference equality means that there are not two objects to

compare. Instead, there are two object references, both of which refer to the same object.

object a = new object();
object b = a;
System.Object.ReferenceEquals(a, b);  //returns true

For predeﬁned value types, the equality operator (==) returns true if the values of its operands are equal, false

