 Chapter 108: Checked and Unchecked

Section 108.1: Checked and Unchecked

C# statements executes in either checked or unchecked context. In a checked context, arithmetic overﬂow raises an

exception. In an unchecked context, arithmetic overﬂow is ignored and the result is truncated.

short m = 32767;
short n = 32767;
int result1 =  checked((short)(m + n));   //will throw an OverflowException
int result2 =  unchecked((short)(m + n)); // will return -2

If neither of these are speciﬁed then the default context will rely on other factors, such as compiler options.

