When you use the yield keyword in a statement, you indicate that the method, operator, or get accessor in which it

appears is an iterator. Using yield to deﬁne an iterator removes the need for an explicit extra class (the class that

holds the state for an enumeration) when you implement the IEnumerable and IEnumerator pattern for a custom

collection type.

Section 120.1: Simple Usage

The yield keyword is used to deﬁne a function which returns an IEnumerable or IEnumerator (as well as their

merable and IEnumerator pattern for a custom

